===Feeding===
[[File:Vermillion flycatcher mitchell lake (14289387962).jpg|thumb|alt=Bird in tree with insect in mouth|With freshly caught insect prey in Texas]]

The vermilion flycatcher feeds mostly on insects such as [[flies]], [[grasshopper]]s and [[beetles]]—though the exact composition of the diet is poorly studied.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Vermilion Flycatcher |url=https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/vermilion-flycatcher |access-date=2024-04-22 |website=Audubon |language=en}}</ref> These are usually taken in mid-air, after a short sally flight from a perch.<ref name=":2" /><ref name="Pizo" /> It is an [[opportunism#Biological|opportunistic]] feeder, and has been observed eating small [[fish]], though it is not known to eat plant material.<ref name=":2" /><ref name="Andrews" /> Bees may also be taken as forage. Non-digestible insect parts are regurgitated as pellets.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|last=Kaufman|first=K.|date=2014|title=Guide to North American Birds: Vermilion Flycatcher|url=https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/vermilion-flycatcher|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410064554/https://www.audubon.org/field-guide/bird/vermilion-flycatcher|archive-date=April 10, 2019|access-date=April 10, 2019|website=Audubon|publisher=[[National Audubon Society]]}}</ref> While waiting for insects, they will sit on thin branches and pump their tail up and down.<ref name=":4" /> While active, about 90% of their day is spent perching, and only 4–11% is spent chasing prey. Once they have spotted prey, they jump up from their perch and give chase. If insects are missed on the first attempt, the bird is capable of quite a nimble flight to catch them. Once caught, the insects may be beaten before being swallowed whole. Occasionally, insects will be caught on the ground. Otherwise, most prey is caught within {{Convert|3|m|ft|abbr=on}} of the ground and rarely above water.<ref name=":2" />

===Survival===
The predators of the vermilion flycatcher are not well known. Unusual reports of predation include by a [[scrub-jay]], and a group of live nestlings eaten by [[fire ant]]s. The oldest recorded individual lived to five and a half years, but otherwise, lifespan data is lacking, as is data about mortality causes. Yearly nesting success (the percentage of laid eggs which were raised to fledglings) in a Texas study varied from 59 to 80%. Half of the lost nests contained eggs and half contained young. The causes of failure included nest abandonment and egg infertility. A similar study in Ecuador showed success rates from 20 to 59%.<ref name=":2" />

Several [[ectoparasite]]s affect the species, ''[[Dermanyssus]]'' mites being common. A 2008 study found that mites did not greatly affect nesting success, nor did nesting reuse greatly enhance mite populations. Fledglings were successfully raised even in infested nests, while nearby, un-infested nests, did not raise any fledglings. Though not directly parasitic, [[Fly|flies]] may lay their eggs in nests, providing a home for their [[larva]].<ref name=":6" />

Although the diseases of the vermilion flycatcher are not well studied, the diseases of the birds of the Galapagos are known, and these diseases may have affected the closely related San Cristóbal flycatcher. Introduced and destructive diseases include [[avian malaria]], [[Marek's disease]], [[Newcastle disease]], and many others.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Wikelski|first1=Martin|last2=Foufopoulos|first2=Johannes|last3=Vargas|first3=Hernan|last4=Snell|first4=Howard|date=2004|title=Galápagos Birds and Diseases: Invasive Pathogens as Threats for Island Species|journal=Ecology and Society|volume=9|issue=1|article-number=art5 |doi=10.5751/ES-00605-090105|jstor=26267654|issn=1708-3087|doi-access=free|hdl=10535/2649|hdl-access=free}}</ref> [[Avian pox]] viruses and crop canker (caused by ''[[Trichomanes gallinae]]'') may have directly contributed to the extinction of the Galapagos sister species.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Vargas |first=H. |date=1996 |title=What is happening to the avifauna of San Cristobal? |url=http://aquaticcommons.org/6788/1/NG_57_1996_Vargas_Avifauna_San_Cristobal.pdf |journal=Noticas de Galapagos |volume=57 |pages=23–24 |issn=0777-6241 |access-date=June 14, 2020 |archive-date=November 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103055137/http://aquaticcommons.org/6788/1/NG_57_1996_Vargas_Avifauna_San_Cristobal.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Relationship to humans==
The vermilion flycatcher is a favorite with [[birdwatching|birders]], but it is not generally kept in [[aviculture]] as the males tend to lose their vermilion coloration when in captivity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.beautyofbirds.com/vermilionflycatchers.html |title=Vermilion Flycatchers |website=Beauty of Birds |url-status=live |access-date=April 16, 2020 |archive-date=March 16, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316064556/http://beautyofbirds.com/vermilionflycatchers.html }}</ref> This is likely a diet-based effect, as maintaining bright red coloration in birds requires substantial quantities of yellow precursor [[zeaxanthin]] molecules which are then [[Metabolism|metabolized]] into red pigment. This acts as an indicator of genetic fitness to potential mates, as a bright male is using his diet-based coloration to show off his ability to survive and catch food.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Lopes |first1=R.| last2=Johnson |first2=J. |last3=Toomey |first3=M. |last4=Ferreira |first4=M. |last5=Araujo |first5=P.|last6=Melo-Ferreira|first6=J.|last7=Andersson|first7=L.|last8=Hill|first8=G.|last9=Corbo|first9=J.|last10=Carneiro|first10=M.|date=2016|title=Genetic Basis for Red Coloration in Birds |journal=[[Current Biology]] |volume=26 |issue=11 |pages=1427–1434 |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2016.03.076|issn=0960-9822|pmc=5125026|pmid=27212400|doi-access=free|bibcode=2016CBio...26.1427L }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Barsh|first=G.|date=2016|title=Evolution: Sex, Diet and Red Ketocarotenoids|journal=Current Biology|volume=26|issue=21|pages=R1145–R1147|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2016.09.032|issn=0960-9822|pmid=27825451|doi-access=free|bibcode=2016CBio...26R1145B }}</ref>

The [[Tucson Bird Alliance]] (formerly Tucson Audubon Society) of [[Tucson, Arizona]], publishes an eponymous journal named for the Vermilion Flycatcher.<ref>{{Cite web|title=''Vermilion Flycatcher''|url=http://tucsonbirds.org/our-work/our-publications/vermilion-flycatcher-magazine/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200223105904/http://tucsonaudubon.org/our-work/our-publications/vermilion-flycatcher-magazine/|archive-date=February 23, 2020|access-date=April 14, 2020|publisher=Tucson [[Tucson Bird Alliance]]}}</ref>

==Status==
Because of its enormous range and sizable population—with a population estimated ranging between 5,000,000 and 50,000,000 individuals—the vermilion flycatcher is listed as a species of [[least concern]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].<ref name="IUCN" /> Its overall numbers are declining; between 1966 and 2007, populations declined an average of 1.7% per year. Texas populations are declining faster, at 2.6% per year. Once prolific in southern [[California]], it has become increasingly rare, although it is expanding into new areas such as [[Florida]] and [[Oklahoma]]. Arizona populations are increasing, at a rate of 2.2% per year. Vermilion flycatchers have adapted to human structures by increasingly nesting in parks and golf courses. However, the increased productivity of these areas may be outweighed by an increased presence of brown-headed cowbirds—whose parasitic young leave less food for flycatcher young—as well as increased nest predation. [[Habitat destruction]] is a major concern for the flycatcher, especially in [[Riparian zone|riparian]] areas. A prime example is along the [[Lower Colorado River Valley]], where changes in water management combined with the destruction of cottonwood-willow riparian habitat have led to the loss of almost all breeding and foraging areas.<ref name=":2" />

The San Cristóbal flycatcher, which was once considered part of the species, was endemic to the Galápagos Islands but went extinct sometime between 1987 and 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2016|title=The First Bird Extinction in Galapagos|work=Durrell |url=https://www.durrell.org/wildlife/news/first-bird-extinction-galapagos/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201002173515/https://www.durrell.org/wildlife/news/first-bird-extinction-galapagos/|archive-date=October 2, 2020|access-date=April 14, 2020|publisher=Durrell Wildlife Conservation Trust}}</ref><ref>Martin W., Johannes F., Hernan V. & Howard S.: ''Galápagos Birds and Diseases: Invasive Pathogens as Threats for Island Species'' ([http://www.wildcru.org/aboutus/people/vargas_pdfs/Diseases-%20Insight%20paper.pdf PDF full text] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516200657/http://www.wildcru.org/aboutus/people/vargas_pdfs/Diseases-%20Insight%20paper.pdf|date=May 16, 2008|title=}}, 384 KB) 2004</ref> The Darwin's flycatcher, which was also once part of the species, is considered a [[near-threatened species]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]].<ref>{{cite iucn |author=BirdLife International. |year=2023 |title=''Pyrocephalus nanus'' |volume=2023 |article-number=e.T103682926A172654604 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2023-1.RLTS.T103682926A172654604.en |access-date=3 July 2024}}</ref>

